<TEI xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" xmlns:frus="http://history.state.gov/frus/ns/1.0"><text><body><div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1933-03-15T18:00:00-05:00" frus:doc-dateTime-min="1933-03-15T18:00:00-05:00" n="533" subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d533">
                        <note rend="inline" type="source">721.23/1409: Telegram</note>
                        <head><hi rend="italic">The <gloss type="from">Secretary of State</gloss> to
                                the Minister in Switzerland</hi> (<persName type="to"><hi rend="italic">Wilson</hi></persName>), <hi rend="italic">at
                                Geneva</hi></head>
                        <opener>
                            <dateline rendition="#right"><placeName><hi rend="smallcaps">Washington</hi></placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1933-03-15T18:00:00-05:00">March 15, 1933—6
                                p.m.</date></dateline>
                        </opener>
                        <p>88. Your 140, March 7, 1 p.m. and 148, March 13, 8 p.m. If and when
                            Council invites the United States to collaborate with the Advisory
                            Committee set up to watch the Leticia situation, you may reply in the
                            same terms as the note quoted in Department’s 86 of March 11, 8
                                p.m.<note n="44" xml:id="d533fn44"><ref target="frus1931-41v01#pg_117"><hi rend="italic">Foreign
                                        Relations</hi>, Japan, 1931–1941, vol. <hi rend="smallcaps">i</hi>, p. 117</ref>.</note> regarding the Far Eastern
                            situation. You will also be guided in your action by paragraph 2 of that
                            instruction.</p>
                        <closer><signed><hi rend="smallcaps">Hull</hi></signed></closer>
                    </div>
                    </body></text></TEI>